Today I woke up and my energy felt a little heavy so I decided I’d go snowboarding to shake it off. While on the chairlift, I realized I forgot my mouth guard which is mandatory for me. Ironically at the same time, I received a text from my Mom that was a screen shot of me, laying in a hospital bed and it said, 6 years ago and immediately after I started crying. 6 years ago I almost lost my life and that will never change. The tears from today were grieving tears because I can still remember a day where I could live my life without worrying about hitting my head. 6 years of carrying the heavy weight of trying to do what makes me happy but it comes with major consequences if I am to ever hit my head again. All of us have our own battles and this one is mine…Grateful to be alive but sometimes resistant to acceptance. 

This post was a reminder to myself that we might feel like we lost who we were but we have grown into something bigger than we could’ve ever imagined. For anyone going through it, I see you, I hear you, I’m here for you. 

Save A Brain saved my life and I hope it saves a million more lives as well. A brain injury can be scary, complex and feel as if you are climbing up the steepest mountain. Working in my trauma is painful yet there are beautiful views from the top of that mountain. Now all we have to do is navigate the terrain as we have the best turns of our life down that same mountain. I can’t say thank you enough for everyone who trusts us, supports us and believes in us and for my group of amazing friends and family for always being my rock. Why was I one of the lucky ones? No clue but I’m ready to get to work and keep living the best second chance ever. 🙏🏼
One week ago we had the best powder day of our season and today it was a record high of 80. Seasonally confused 🤷🏼‍♀️

New Episode out with @kelseyboyer 🎙️From Competitive Snowboarder to Traumatic Brain Injury Survivor to Finding a New Purpose

Join @emilieuttrup on this episode of Resurface, where she sits down with Kelsey Boyer, a former competitive snowboarder whose career was cut short by a traumatic brain injury six years ago. Kelsey takes us on a remarkable journey, from her rise to the top of the snowboarding world to how her life changed after her injury. She candidly shares insights into the challenges she faced, such as depression and anger, and the decisions she made to overcome them, including starting her own nonprofit organization, @saveabrain 💙
Kelsey’s journey is truly inspiring, and her resilience and determination shine through as she discusses the obstacles she faced and how she overcame them. This episode is a must-listen for anyone looking for inspiration or facing their own challenges, as Kelsey’s story proves that we are never alone. Don’t miss out on hearing Kelsey’s unique and inspiring journey. Tune in now to this episode of Resurface. Link in bio 🎧

This season I started dabbling more with leaving the ground again. Stumbled upon this moment in time from the best powder day of the season.
🎥: @melissariitano

It’s been incredibly hard to find words lately and it’s wild what you can hide behind a smile. This winter I hit my head for the first time in a while. What I didn’t realize was everything that I would encounter that led me to this moment. My symptoms, anxiety and PTSD were all triggered and instead of dealing with them, I masked them. I didn’t want to be the girl with a head injury again so I simply pretended that everything was fine. I have been suffocating under this mask in fear of how people will look at me. Will everyone see me differently and think I’m not capable of running a business? So instead I went 4 months and completely lost myself, my voice and purpose which led to me hitting the floor in an unexpected panic attack. I’m not here for pity, I’m here to use my voice and say that a brain injury does not define you. Anyone who deals with head trauma or has been around it, I applaud you, you are resilient and a warrior. Don’t quiet your voice in fear of others, BE FREE. Accept what has happened, be proud of how far you have come and take off that heavy mask. 

Im writing this with a fresh perspective and channeling what I felt like I was missing from SAB as a traumatic brain injury survivor myself. I need @saveabrain just as much as everyone else and that’s why we must keep going. There’s no rule book of how this is suppose to be done but I’m so excited to share KB & SAB 2.0 with you soon. 
📸: @nirvanaortanez
